		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:25:"Was Robin Hood a Marxist?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"http://libertarianstandard.com/2014/06/16/was-robin-hood-a-marxist/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:76:"http://libertarianstandard.com/2014/06/16/was-robin-hood-a-marxist/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 16 Jun 2014 14:37:33 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"History";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"Libertarian Theory";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Pop Culture";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:39:"http://libertarianstandard.com/?p=13499";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:367:"Simon Schama could use a dose of classical-liberal theory. Most of us can be forgiven for knowing Marxist theory better than the liberal tradition &#8212; it&#8217;s hard not to drink Marxism in with our schooling and culture &#8212; but popular historical narrative really does suffer by the omission of the &#34;bourgeois historians&#34; whom Marx himself [&#8230;]";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"BK Marcus";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2825:"<a class="featured_image_link" href="http://libertarianstandard.com/2014/06/16/was-robin-hood-a-marxist/"><img width="300" height="225" src="http://libertarianstandard.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/FreemanRobinHood300.jpg" class="alignright wp-post-image" alt="FreemanRobinHood300" /></a><p>Simon Schama could use a dose of classical-liberal theory. Most of us can be forgiven for knowing Marxist theory better than the liberal tradition &mdash; it&#8217;s hard not to drink Marxism in with our schooling and culture &mdash; but popular historical narrative really does suffer by the omission of the &quot;bourgeois historians&quot; whom Marx himself credits as the precursors of his class theory.</p>
<p>In the BBC TV series <i>A History of Britain</i>, Schama asks about the English Peasants&#8217; Revolt of 1381, &quot;Was this a class war, then?&quot; (A term, he explains parenthetically that &quot;we&#8217;re not supposed to use since the official burial of Marxism.&quot;) A pause, while the camera angle changes to closeup. &quot;Yes,&quot; he says plainly. &quot;It was.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Not surprisingly,&quot; writes Schama in the print version of <i>A History of Britain</i>, &quot;it was in the second half of the fourteenth century that the legends of Robin Hood &hellip; first became genuinely popular.&quot;</p>
<p>But as I write in <a href="http://www.fee.org/the_freeman/detail/class-war-in-the-time-of-robin-hood">&quot;Class War in the Time of Robin Hood&quot;</a> in today&#8217;s <i>Freeman</i>, Schama is appealing to the wrong class theory if he wants to explain the mindset of the commoners marching on London in the 14th century.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m far from the first to offer a libertarian revision of Robin Hood&#8217;s politics, but where I focus on the ideology of his earliest historical audience, most other treatments focus on the particulars of the legend.</p>
<p>Some examples:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://left-liberty.net/?p=429">&#8220;Robin Hood Revisionism&#8221;</a> by Karl Hess, <i>Libertarian Forum</i>, 1969</li>
<li><a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/maurapennington/2012/03/26/robin-hood-has-always-been-a-libertarian-hero/">&quot;Robin Hood Has Always Been A Libertarian Hero&quot;</a> by Maura Pennington, Forbes.com, 2012</li>
</ul>
<p>On the other hand, Ayn Rand seems to have been happy to leave Robin Hood to the socialists:</p>
<p>&quot;It is said,&quot; <a href="http://readingregistry.wordpress.com/2009/07/10/ragnar-danneskjold-on-robin-hood/">Rand has Ragnar Danneskj&ouml;ld concede in <i>Atlas Shrugged</i></a>, that Robin Hood &quot;fought against the looting rulers and returned the loot to those who had been robbed, but that is not the meaning of the legend which has survived.</p>
<p>What do you think: is Robin Hood worth claiming for our tradition?</p>
